<font color="#FF0000">BENIFITING SOCIETY.</font><br>
<tt>Mon Oct 20 12:18:40 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
&lt;&lt;. . . So, I'll re-phrase it; how can our society benefit from our experiences and commitment to each other that we exhibited in 'Nam?&gt;&gt;<br>
   John,<br><br>
   Heavy.  Serious question, and deserves a serious reply.  I can only give it a try.<br><br>
      Does it  assumes [?] that society wants our experience and thinks our experience benicial?  And that we are capable of inluencing society as currently organized?<br><br>
   To cynical old me the first appears doubtful at best, and the second is up-hill.  Steep hill.  <br><br>
    I don't mean that we should say F*** it and give up.  But influencing &quot;society&quot; does sound rathrer grandose, but I do understand the sentiment.<br><br>
   The best approach is to begin at the personal level--with our children and relatives.  Talk to them.  I remember the Civil War vets talking when I was a kid, and my Dad's Army fellow NCOs chatting about the [pre WW 2] Army.  I learned values---with out going to school.<br><br>
      Next up the scale would be the educatinal system, but one shouldn't expect too much from a system that cranks out students who haven't the foggest idea of their own country's history, and are incapable of reading about it. <br>
    The &quot;system&quot; is the enemy.  Really.  It doesn't want our experience and will discourge any involvement.<br><br>
    Again, in my youth, the schools [in the South] were heavy on history---lots on the State, plus national. Had Washington's and Lee's photo in the classroom. [VA]  They took little-bitty fellows on field trips where at a local battlefield, the teacher would say:  &quot;On this spot, five Gallant Southern soldiers withstood the attack by a hundred thieving Yankees.&quot;  I am exagerating the quote, but we went there and learned about commitment and sacrifice.<br><br>
      Can you imagine anything like that happing today?  Is it happing anywhere?  How do you expect us to influece society in the current atmosphere?  We can.<br><br>
      Sad to say, that's no longer the case, and the students  acheivement level seems to hover around the &quot;put on a condum&quot; and operate the &quot;remote-control.&quot;    <br><br>
    Self-Esteem, not self-sacifice is taught.  Of course, being &quot;non-judgemental&quot; is the first commandment.<br><br>
   Still that's the place that will pay off if anyone can make them pay attention.  And it is something that can be accomplished best at the local level--if one can put up with the heavy--heavy, opposition you'll encounter.<br><br>
     Letters to the editors of local papers is another tool, but again, don't expect a lot of space, but trying counts.<br>
  <br>
      Running for political office is a fine way to go, if one has the desire and resources.<br><br>
      I guess what I am saying comes down to commitment and involment.  Easy for me to say.  <br>
    Still like someone once said:<br>
 &quot;It's better to light one candle then to curse the darkness.&quot;<br><br>
Andy<br>
    
